ish, Scottish: (i) variant of   Gethin  , with English genitival or excrescent  <i>-s</i>. (ii) possibly also a variant of   Gitton   (1) with post-medieval excrescent  <i>-s</i>.","2  Irish: if not the Welsh name in Ireland, this name may have been adopted as a shortened form of  <b>Mag Eiteagáin</b>,  see  McGettigan  ."]}]},{"name":"Malcolm","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Anglicized form of the medieval Gaelic name <i>Mael Coluim</i> ‘devotee of St Columba’. Columba was a 6th-century monk of Irish origin who played a leading part in the conversion to Christianity of Scotland and northern England;  see also  Callum   and   Colm .  He has always been one of the most popular saints in Scotland, but in the Middle Ages it was felt to be presumptuous to give the names of saints directly to children; instead their blessing was invoked by prefixing the name with <i>mael</i> ‘devotee of’ or <i>gille</i> ‘servant of’. Since the 1930s the given name has been used widely in the English-speaking world, not just by those with Scottish connections."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Malcolm Kettins was born about 1185, in Kettins, Angus, Scotland, United Kingdom as the son of Walter Kettins and wife Walter Kettins. He married wife Malcolm Kettins before 1220, in Europe. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died about 1240, in his hometown, at the age of 57."},"et":{"about 1185–abt 1240":"umbes 1185–umbes 1240","1185–1240":"1185–1240","–Female":"Surnud","1220–1270":"1220–1270","1140–1190":"1140–1190","1190":"1190","before 1220":"enne 1220","before 1185":"enne 1185","1220":"1220","abt 1240":"umbes 1240","1240":"1240","1185":"1185","1140":"1140","about 1220":"umbes 1220","1270":"1270","about 1185":"umbes 1185","Angus, Scotland":"Angus, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Europe":"Europe","Kettins, Forfarshire, Scotland":"Kettins, Angus, Šotimaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1185–abt 1240":"